metadata.name: Haste Season #30
metadata.description:
“Do not spoil the wonder with haste.”
― J.R.R. Tolkien, The Return of the King

This piece is here to point us to the fact that Haste season is upon us. It is the season when more people are moving than usual, and the dynamic movement of each person gives our world a wonderful composition. But it also increases the chance that something really bad will happen. Let's ensure that the chaotic image of cities, crowds, and haste that is before us becomes the perfect image of chaos. Image of people who love and respect one another. Image of wonder that we can be.

Made with P5js.
Bajiru, December 2022.

metadata.name: ThreeSixFive #15
metadata.description:
//////////////////////////////////////
           "ThreeSixFive"
//////////////////////////////////////

The code generates a main grid based on "Number Points" feature on which it creates the entire composition.
An internal clock is displayed as animated white arcs to represent the passing of time, in addition a new cell of the grid are filled every second.

Features:
- "Number Points": 90% chance of 12 Points, 10% chance of 24 Points.
- "Linear Mode": 0.5% chance of TRUE linear mode (the composition will be slightly different).

metadata.name: Glossolalia #222
metadata.description:
This series is ultimately about catharsis. The compositions can be chaotic and maybe even a little messy, but they also can be vibrant and diverse… which is really what this is trying to celebrate: diversity and expression.

Simply, it’s about the emotions associated with whatever frees you.

Please see the linked fxtext article (on the main project page) for a more in-depth dissection of the concept. It’s less of a technical discussion, and more about the experience of the artist, and how it became linked with the feelings they associate with the art.

In live mode:

For higher resolutions, you can append “&density=2” to the url to double the size, “&density=3” to triple, and so on.
(This is highly recommended.)

To adjust grain, you can append “&grain=##” to the url. 40 is the default, and 0 will remove it completely.

metadata.name: The Artifact #112
metadata.description:
An archaeological artifact from the future, when many everyday objects are produced by generative algorithms. Some artifacts are in one piece, and others are fragmented. The color palettes are named after the rivers where artifacts in this design have first been discovered.

URL and interactive features:

- Append &r=<number> to the URL to change the image resolution. For example, &r=0.5 will halve the pixel count along both width and height, and &r=2 will double it.

- Append &d=<number> to the URL to change the pixel density. For example, &d=0.3 will generate a very quick, coarse render, and &d=2 will generate very fine stippling.

- Append &p to the URL to reveal detailed parameter settings used for the artwork.

- Append &h to the URL to suppress the notification that rendering is in progress.

- Press 's' in the live view to save the rendered image as a png.

The generative code is written in plain JavaScript. Polygon boundaries are determined via t-SNE, which is implemented in AssemblyScript and compiled to WebAssembly (WASM) for maximum performance. No external libraries have been used. Licensed CC0.

Author:
Claus O. Wilke
https://clauswilke.com/art
https://twitter.com/clauswilke

metadata.name: Obliques #12
metadata.description:
Obliques are a reinterpretation of Parallels, a collection of AI generated color fields by Marc Maurer. Many of the pieces in that collection are CC0, which basically means they can be reused for other projects, like this one.

Obliques takes artifacts from Parallels and uses them as brushes, painting slices of the original image on the canvas in a (hopefully) pleasant, chaotic way.

About 10% will be "Glitched".

The "Source Material" property will tell you the name of piece that it is using.

You can see Marc Maurer's Parallels project here:
https://objkt.com/collection/KT1TiSEcASGD19SW8bmqrqgSgCBkwXqDdTJ1

Obliques are also CC0, so feel free use anything here in other projects.

You can read more about CC0 here:
https://creativecommons.org/share-your-work/public-domain/cc0/

G : Toggle Grain
M : Toggle Matte
S : Save Image
1 -> 6 : Set pixel density
(Default pixel density is 1 @ 2000x2000)

metadata.name: Dashed Migration #33
metadata.description:
This is an ode to dashed lines and vector graphics.

The artwork is an animated SVG generated with Javascript.
All the animation is described and handled within the SVG.

Exports:
• animated SVG
• plotter-ready SVG
• PNG

Controls:
• 'SPACE'/click - play/pause animation
In Live view
• 'f' - fullscreen
• 'c' - show/hide cursor
• 'e' - open the export menu
On touchscreens, the export menu can be opened with a long-press.

fx(hash) Generative Token by loackme
